<p>*Assumes 8% capital return and 2% income return. One-half of capital return is
unrealized. The realized gain is split equally between short-term and long-term
gains.  The returns for bond and money market funds are assumed to be 100% income
return. This example is for illustrative purposes only and does not imply returns
available on any particular investment.  If you translate the above into dollars
and cents it becomes even more clear.  All three investors made the same decision
a decade ago: Each invested $15,000, split evenly between the three funds.  When
the time came to redeem the accounts, Investor A had $27,953, Investor B had $26,101,
and Investor C had $25, 127.  As you can now see, a fund's advertised return can
look a lot different from your after-tax return, depending on your individual tax
bracket.</p>

<p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="IncomeVersusCapitalGains"></a>
<h2>Income vs. Capital Gains</h2>

<p>In 1997, Congress boosted the attraction of taxable mutual fund accounts by
cutting an important tax rate. The tax rate on most long-term capital gains
dropped to 10% (from 15%) for people in the lowest federal income tax bracket;
for all other taxpayers, the tax rate dropped to 20% (from 28%).</p>

<p>To understand how this should affect your investment strategy, you must first
understand how your funds make money.  Mutual funds generally distribute all
its earnings to its shareholders, which may be liable for taxes on those earnings.
Distributions are taxable as either income or capital gains:</p>

<ul>
    <li>If a fund manager makes more profits than losses on the sale of securities held in the portfolio for more than
        a year, a long-term capital gains results. Those profits (adjusted for any net short-term capital losses) are
        distributed to you at year-end, and you owe a capital gains tax of 10% or 20%, depending on your income. Funds
        do not distribute capital gains every year. When there are more losses than gains from securities sales, those
        losses can be carried forward to offset gains in future years.</li>
    <li>If the fund receives interest and dividend payments on its securities, those will be distributed to you as
        ordinary income (after fund expenses are deducted), and you will owe income tax at your ordinary income tax
        rate (from 15% to 39.6%).</li>
</ul>

<p>A top tax rate of 20% is obviously more desirable than a top rate of 39.6%.
For investors in higher tax brackets, therefore, it makes sense to invest in
funds whose distributions result from capital gains, not income.</p>

<p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="IsYourFundTaxFriendly"></a>
<h2>Is Your Fund Tax Friendly?</h2>

<p>At the end of the day, it is not your fund's total return that matters but the
after-tax return that you pocket. When determining whether a fund may reduce
your tax liability, consider these factors:</p>

<ul>
    <li><em>Holdings:</em> Does your fund own taxable bonds? If it is a stock fund, is producing income one of its
        main objectives? Such funds are likely to make regular distributions to you that will be taxed as ordinary
        income. On the other hand, if your fund holds low-yielding growth stocks, you may face fewer income
        distributions and more capital gains distributions, which are taxed at a lower rate.</li>
    <li><em>Turnover Rate:</em> Does your fund maintain a buy-and-hold approach, or does the fund frequently buy and
        sell securities? The best indication of a fund's trading activity is its turnover rate, which measures the
        frequency with which securities are bought and sold during a year. A high turnover rate in a strong market
        increases the likelihood that a fund will realize its gains and distribute them to shareholders.</li>
</ul>

<p>Taxes are not entirely avoidable. When you redeem your fund shares, you will owe
capital gains taxes, assuming the investment appreciated in value. But you want
to avoid a heavy tax burden while you own your shares. Those annual tax bites eat
away at the amount of money you have available to invest and grow over time.
Traditional individual retirement accounts are attractive because taxes are deferred
until you retire.  A tax-friendly fund in a taxable account should offer the same
benefit - a minimal tax bite, or no taxes at all, until you withdraw your money
from the account.</p>

<p>By investigating a fund's holdings and turnover rate, you can gain some control
over taxes on your investments and, ultimately, your return. The following table
may help you weigh tax considerations when selecting funds:</p>

<table class="info-table">
    <tr>
        <td class="label" align="center" valign="bottom">
            Type of Fund
        </td>
        <td class="label" align="center" valign="bottom">
            Potential for<br>Income Taxes
        </td>
        <td class="label" align="center" valign="bottom">
            Potential for<br>Capital Gains<br>or Losses
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td class="label" align="left" valign="bottom">
