        <p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="HowDoesCapitalGainsWork"></a>
<h2>How Does Capital Gains Work?</h2>

<p>As an owner of mutual fund shares, you can be taxed two ways: on the earnings
a fund makes while you own its shares and on the profits you make when you
sell or exchange shares.</p>

<p>You are in control of when you sell shares, but you don't control decisions made
by the fund's manager (although you can select a fund for its tax-friendliness).
This has been a hard lesson for investors in many growth funds, who have gone for
years paying little or no taxes and are increasingly being hit with high tax bills
as the bull market matures.</p>

<p>Why have more funds generated increasing tax liabilities? The explanation comes
from how capital gains are managed, or not managed. Capital gains come in two
forms, unrealized and realized:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Unrealized Gains are gains on paper only and are not taxed until the gains are realized and distributed to
        shareholders. A fund can post a large return and not trigger taxes for its shareholders if the shares in which
        it invests appreciate and are not sold. Compared with funds with high turnover rates, funds with low turnover
        rates, such as index funds, tend to have more unrealized gains.</li>
    <li>Realized Gains occur when an investment that has appreciated in value is sold. At that point, the profit is
        taxable as a capital gain. Managers can offset profits from the sale of one stock with losses from the sale of
        another stock, a balancing act that reduces the net taxable gain. But in a lengthy bull market, it is more
        difficult to find losers to offset winners. Investors in funds that are not managed with an eye on tax
        consequences are learning this drawback of the bull market.</li>
</ul>

<p>One confusing trait of capital gains distributions is that they can occur in a
year when the fund has a poor return. Assume that a growth fund is heavily
invested in a strong-performing sector and its managers stick with their
winning stocks in 1998 and 1999. The amount of trading in the portfolio is
minimal and the returns are strong. In early 2000, the fund managers decide to
sell their winning stocks and invest in stocks they think have better potential
for gains, but the new stocks initially are disappointing. Here is the result:</p>

<table class="info-table">

