<p>Needless to say, investors attracted to the fund for its strong long-term
performance would not be happy with a tax bill of $2 for every share they
own (assuming a capital gains tax of 20%: $10 x 0.2=$2). It can happen.
That's why it pays to understand the investment strategy of the fund you buy.</p>

<p>The table below shows that capital gains have a dramatic impact on investment
performance. It compares two $10,000 investments, each of which returned 10%
annually over a 20-year period.</p>

<p>Fund A made capital gains distribution every year. Fund B had a tax-efficient
fund manager who never paid a capital gains distribution. The Fund A investor
reinvested distributions, minus taxes, every year and then redeemed the account
after 20 years. The Fund B investor redeemed the account after 20 years. The
Fund B investor redeemed the account at the same time and paid taxes on 20
years of gains.</p>

<p>By paying taxes in a lump sum at the end of the investment's life rather than
every year, the Fund B investor kept $6,897 more than the investor in Fund A.</p>

<p>The bottom line: By deferring taxes, you can enhance your investment returns over time.</p>

<p>The Impact of Capital Gains Distributions on Total Return: In each case, the 10%
return was made up of 2% income distributions and 8% capital gains distributions.
The table assumes a tax rate of 28% on income distributions and 20% on capital
gains distributions. This example is for illustrative purposes only and does not
imply return available on any particular investment.</p>

