<a name="TipsToLimitYourTaxes"></a>
<h2>Tips to Limit Your Taxes</h2>

<p>Here are some ways you can "tax proof" your portfolio:</p>

<ul>
    <li><em>Choose Index Funds:</em> Index funds buy and hold the securities in a specific market index (or a
        representative sample of the index). As a result, they tend to have lower turnover than actively managed funds,
        which means they are less likely to pass along taxable gains to investors.</li>
    <li><em>Consider Tax Managed Funds:</em> Tax-managed funds are designed for taxable investors; they focus on
        after-tax returns and employ special strategies to hold down taxable gains. In addition to using indexing to
        limit turnover, tax-managed funds may practice "loss-harvesting," offsetting realized gains by selling
        securities with losses. They may also encourage long-term investing by charging redemption fees to shareholders
        that leave the fund soon after investing. Such investors can force fund managers to sell shares to meet
        redemption's, triggering taxable gains.</li>
    <li><em>Weigh Market Capitalization:</em> Compared with large-capitalization funds, small-capitalization funds
        as a group tend to realize more capital gains. Small-cap stocks tend to "graduate" into larger-cap stocks
        over time and must be sold because they no longer belong in a small-cap fund. However, small-cap stocks
        generally have lower dividends.</li>
    <li><em>Weigh Growth Versus Value:</em> Compared with growth funds, value funds generally have higher dividends,
        which are taxed at your ordinary income tax rate. In addition, value funds tend to pass along more realized
        capital gains, all else being equal. That's because a successful value manager generally buys out-of-favor
        stocks then sells them when they become winners. In contrast, a growth manager picks stocks that are believed
        to offer good growth potential and may sell them when their prospects fade. As a result, you might prefer to
        hold value funds in your retirement accounts, where their dividends and capital gains will not be taxed every
        year, and growth funds in your taxable funds in your taxable accounts.</li>
    <li><em>Buy and Hold:</em> The more you sell or exchange shares, the more capital gains you are likely to
        realize. Minimize the trading you do, and if you must sell shares, seek long-term gains (profits on
        investments held more than a year), which are taxed at lower rates. You might also offset some gains by
        selling shares that have lost value during your ownership.</li>
</ul>

<p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="TaxCuttingStrategies"></a>
<h2>Tax-Cutting Strategies</h2>

<p>Simply by being a tax-conscious investor, you can keep significantly more of the return on your investment. You
    can minimize taxes on your portfolio in four basic ways: </p>

<ul>
    <li><em>Delaying Taxes with Retirement Accounts:</em> If an investment is considered tax-deferred under Internal
        Revenue Service rules, your investment earnings are not taxed until they are withdrawn from the tax-deferred
        account. Examples include individual retirement accounts, 401(k) and 403(b) plans, and variable annuities.</li>
    <li><em>Reducing Taxes with Roth IRAs:</em> Contributions are not deductible, but the earnings grow tax-free in
        Roth IRAs (available since the 1998-tax year). You generally do not owe any tax when you withdraw your money
        from these accounts.</li>
    <li><em>Reducing Taxes with Municipal Bonds:</em> Tax-free bonds issued by state or local political subdivisions
        generate income that is exempt from federal (and often state and local) income taxes.</li>
    <li><em>Controlling Taxes with Tax-Efficient Stock Funds:</em> Tax-efficient funds are managed to maximize your
        after-tax return by minimizing taxable distributions. Tactics include low-turnover investment strategies and
        the carefully managed selling of shares.</li>
</ul>

<p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="DelayingTaxesWithRetirmentAccounts"></a>
<h2>Delaying Taxes with Retirement Accounts</h2>

<p>Retirement accounts enable you to defer paying tax on your investments, which boosts your returns in the long run.</p>

<p>The table below compares the growth of a $50,000 investment in a taxable account
with the growth of an equivalent investment in a tax-deferred retirement plan.
It illustrates that investors who defer taxes may fare better, even after they
have paid taxes on a lump-sum distribution, than investors who pay taxes every
year. Note that constant tax rates are assumed before and after retirement.
If you are subject to a lower tax rate in retirement, you will benefit even more
from tax deferral. Of course, if you are subject to a higher tax rate in
retirement, tax deferral will be less beneficial.</p>

<p>The Tax-Deferred Advantage:</p>

