<p>The table assumes an 8% average annual return for 20 years. It assumes that all
taxes on the unsheltered and the tax-deferred accounts are paid annually while
taxes on the tax-deferred account are paid in a lump sum. The data are for
illustration only and do not imply returns that may be earned on an investment
made today.</p>

<p>The following are the three most common types of retirement accounts:</p>

<h3>Traditional Individual Retirement Accounts:</h3>

<p>If you are under the age of 70-1/2, you can contribute up to $2,000 of earned income each year to a traditional IRA.
    Your earnings on the account grow tax-deferred until you begin making withdrawals, which are penalty-free after the
    age of 59-1/2.</p>

<p>Your contributions are tax-deductible if you are not an active participant in an employer-sponsored plan (such as a
    401[k] plan) or if your modified adjusted gross income is below a certain threshold. (For 1999, the threshold is
    $31,000 for single filers and $51,000 for joint filers. Partial deductions are allowed on incomes up to $41,000
    and $61,000, respectively.)</p>

<p>Contributions for a given year must be made no later than the tax-filing deadline for that tax year, which for
    most taxpayers is April 15 of the following year.</p>

<p>Once you begin withdrawing from your IRA, you pay tax at your ordinary income tax rate on your deductible
    contributions and earnings. (You were taxed on your nondeductible contributions when you made them.) If you
    expect your tax rate to decline in retirement, traditional IRAs are an attractive option, because you avoid
    a higher tax rate on your investment while you are working and pay at a lower rate after you retire. If you
    expect your tax rate to increase or stay the same in retirement, however, consider a Roth IRA.</p>

<h3>401(k) Plans:</h3>

<p>If you are building a retirement nest egg, the best place to begin is your employer-sponsored 401(k) retirement
    plan, if one is available to you. Many plans offer matching contributions: For every dollar you contribute (up
    to a certain percentage of your income), your employer may match a percentage of your contribution. For example,
    if the match is 50 cents per dollar, that means your contribution earns a 50% return even before it is invested.</p>

<p>Your 401(k) is further enhanced by Uncle Sam; Any contributions are made on a pre-tax basis. That means your taxable
    pay is reduced, and so is your tax. For example, if you receive a $1,000 paycheck and you are in the 28% tax
    bracket, you lose $280 to federal tax. But if you contribute $50 of that paycheck to your 401(k), you will owe
    only $266 in tax today (28% of $950).</p>

<h3>Variable Annuities:</h3>

<p>A variable annuity can be part of a qualified plan, such as an IRA, which allows tax-deductible contributions. A
    non-qualified annuity is after-tax, so you receive no up-front tax benefits as you do with a 401(k) plan or a
    deductible IRA. Like IRAs and 401(k)s, your variable annuity investment grows tax-deferred, and withdrawals of
    investment earnings are taxed at your ordinary income tax rate during retirement. Variable annuities can be
    invested in stock and bond funds set up specifically for annuity investments.</p>

<p>Variable annuities are part investment vehicle and part insurance product. They guarantee that, when you die, your
    beneficiary(s) will get back at least what you invested, even if the portfolio lost money.  Most studies suggest
    that an investor needs to stay with a variable annuity for ten years or longer before the benefits of tax deferral
    outweigh the extra costs.</p>

<p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="LockingInTaxesWithRothIRAs"></a>
<h2>Locking in Taxes with Roth IRA's</h2>

<p>Roth individual retirement accounts offer several advantages over traditional IRAs:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Contributions are not deductible but the account grows tax-free. Withdrawals are tax-free once you reach age
        59-1/2 and the account is at least five years old.</li>
    <li>You can withdraw an amount equal to your contribution at any time without additional tax or penalty.</li>
    <li>You can contribute even after age 70-1/2, as long as you have earned income.</li>
    <li>There are no required minimum distributions (RMDs) during the lifetime of the owner, meaning the account can
        grow tax-free as long as its owner desires.</li>
    <li>A beneficiary who inherits the account can make tax-free withdrawals, if certain conditions are met. A spouse
        who is the sole primary beneficiary can assume ownership of the account, gaining all account privileges and
        avoiding RMDs.</li>
</ul>

<p>If you believe your income tax rate will rise in retirement or stay the same,
the Roth IRA offers significant tax advantages. One point is clear: If you are
not eligible to deduct your traditional IRA contribution, a Roth IRA is
preferable to a nondeductible IRA. Why invest in a nondeductible traditional
IRA and pay income tax after you retire when you can take proceeds from a Roth
IRA tax-free?</p>

<p>You can contribute up to $2,000 of your earned income (from wages or a salary)
each year to a Roth IRA if your modified adjusted growth income (AGI) is
$95,000 or less (for single filers) or $150,000 or less (for joint filers).</p>

<h3>Roth Conversions</h3>

<p>The benefits of a Roth IRA are available not only to those opening new accounts.
You can also convert an existing traditional IRA to a Roth IRA.</p>

<p>When you convert, you pay the tax owed at the time of conversion, in essence
purchasing the right to withdraw the IRAs contents tax-free (once the amount
is five years old and you have reached age 59-1/2). When you convert a
deductible IRA, you pay tax on the original contribution and earnings; when you
convert a nondeductible IRA, you pay tax only on the earnings. (The conversion
tax is harder to calculate if your IRA includes both deductible and
non-deductible contributions.)</p>

<p>To be eligible to convert a traditional IRA to a Roth IRA, you must file a
single or joint tax return reporting an AGI of $100,000 or less.</p>

<p>Whether you choose a Roth IRA or a traditional IRA depends on whether you think
tax rates will rise by the time you retire and when you expect to make
withdrawals from the account. If you think tax rates will rise, you may want to
convert all your traditional IRAs to Roth IRAs and pay tax up front. If you
believe tax rates will decline, a traditional IRA makes more sense because you
won't pay tax until you retire. Future tax rates are uncertain, so you might
want to convert a portion of your traditional IRAs to Roth IRAs to "hedge"
against diverse changes in tax rates.</p>

<h3>Education IRAs</h3>

<p>Despite its name, education IRAs are not intended for retirement savings.
Instead, they help parents (and other interested parties) invest toward a
child's higher education.</p>

<p>Withdrawals from Education IRAs are tax-free if they are used to pay for
qualified higher-education expenses before the beneficiary reaches age 30.
Contributions are nondeductible and are limited to $500 per child per calendar
year from the child's birth to his or her 18th birthday. Contributions are
phased out if you are a single filer with an AGI of $95,000 to $110,000 or a
joint filer with an AGI of $150,000 to $160,000.</p>

<p><a class="LinkInternal" href="#TopOfPage">Back to top of page</a></p>

<a name="ReducingTaxesWithMunicipalBonds"></a>
<h2>Reducing Taxes with Municipal Bonds</h2>

<p>Municipal bond funds provide income that is exempt from federal income tax.
The trade-off is that they pay less income than taxable bond funds. If your
primary goal is income (that is, you invest in bond funds rather than stock
funds) and you are in a higher tax bracket, this trade-off may appeal to you
because municipal bond funds are likely to increase your after-tax income.</p>

<p>The table below can help you determine whether municipal bond funds make sense
for you. It shows the taxable yields at various federal income rates that are
equivalent to tax-exempt yields o 3% to 6%. For example, if your income is
taxed at the 36% rate and you invest in a municipal bond fund with a 5% yield,
a taxable bond fund would have to yield at least 7.81% to be more attractive.
(You may also want to consider whether you save anything on state income tax.)</p>

<p>NOTE: When you compare municipal and taxable bond funds, make sure they invest
in bonds with similar maturities and credit quality. Getting a better rate on
taxable fund may not pay off if you have taken on a greater amount of risk.</p>

